rmalized": true, "mention": "immunoglobulin family", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9959612488746643, "span": {"begin": 707, "end": 728}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3547"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IgSF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9933080077171326, "span": {"begin": 730, "end": 734}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:25555"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "N", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986189603805542, "span": {"begin": 765, "end": 766}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:102723407", "102724971"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IgV", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9862182140350342, "span": {"begin": 801, "end": 804}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30039"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "C", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988358616828918, "span": {"begin": 819, "end": 820}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:11326"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "immunoglobulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.5119039416313171, "span": {"begin": 839, "end": 853}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7441"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IgC", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9845602512359619, "span": {"begin": 855, "end": 858}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:55180"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Lin et", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8887403607368469, "span": {"begin": 868, "end": 874}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:96610"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IgV domain", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926061034202576, "span": {"begin": 918, "end": 928}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5133"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "PD-1 receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9946607947349548, "span": {"begin": 962, "end": 975}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T lymphocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6758460998535156, "span": {"begin": 1006, "end": 1019}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "B lymphocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6578662395477295, "span": {"begin": 1065, "end": 1078}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999629259109497, "span": {"begin": 1099, "end": 1105}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor&nbsp;cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8397054672241211, "span": {"begin": 1107, "end": 1123}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8989114165306091, "span": {"begin": 1107, "end": 1112}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9958025813102722, "span": {"begin": 1213, "end": 1218}}, {"id": ["mesh:C040216"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TME", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9940117597579956, "span": {"begin": 1237, "end": 1240}}], "text": "PD-L1 (Programmed Death-Ligand 1, or B7-H1/CD274) is known to be a promising therapeutic target in the development of anti-tumor treatments. This ligand can be expressed in several forms: cytoplasmic, membrane-bound, soluble, or in extracellular vesicles. Based on current knowledge, the membrane form is the most well-documented, particularly for inhibiting T cell activity (Lin et al., 2024). Its physiological role is to bind to PD1 (or CD279), its receptor on immune cells, giving it an essential immunosuppressive role (Butte et al., 2007). This is why this ligand is well studied for treatment related to immunosuppressive disease (Tomlins et al., 2023).  PD-L1 is a membrane protein belonging to the immunoglobulin family (IgSF). It has two main domains: an N-terminal variable immunoglobulin (IgV) domain and a C-terminal constant immunoglobulin (IgC) domain (Lin et al., 2008) (Jiang et al., 2019). It is the IgV domain that allows interaction with the PD-1 receptor, which is mainly expressed on T lymphocytes but also present in slightly lower levels on B lymphocytes.  In the context of cancer, tumor&nbsp;cells overexpress this ligand, which contributes to immune escape and the establishment of the Tumor MicroEnvironment (TME) (Riella et al., 2012).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 22:02:03 +0000 2026"}